text.tspan: Despite having a reputation for being weak
in the eyes of outsiders, the Nine Fingers
are formidable in battle due to their close-
combat skills and loyalty to one another.
They often employ surprise attacks to draw
their opponents into hand-to-hand combat.
The Nine Fingers, a group consisting of
gladiators and other individuals who fled
the Fidelian Empire, are not well-versed in
the use of firearms. Instead, they rely on
hand-to-hand combat techniques, such as
using swords, shields, and whips, which
they learned while fighting in the empire's
arenas.
The Nine Fingers, a group of
mercenaries led by Leopart the 3rd
and eight comrades, will do whatever
it takes to survive, including stealing
weapons and money, robbing other
groups, and fishing for food. They are
not afraid of taking risks to obtain
essential supplies like food, water,
and weapons.
Leopart the 3rd, a champion gladiator, fled the
empire in search of freedom and joined forces with
other slave fighters in the same arena, destroying the
space and stealing weapons from the empire.
Gladiators were slave entertainers who
fought in the empire's arenas for the
enjoyment of the noble class. They were
treated as disposable goods and were
expected to be used up and discarded
quickly.
The Nine Fingers is a group of nine
people, led by Leopart the 3rd,
who fled the Fidelian Empire. It is
composed of gladiators from
Fidelian's arenas, slave workers,
and a few other civilians who
joined along the way.
New beginnings
Biff was always worried about being betrayed
and the empire did not care about who became
the leader of the Hunters, so he did not train
his subordinates to be too strong. He knew that
having subordinates with very high combat
abilities could be dangerous for him, given the
nature of the missions that the Hunters
accepted from the empire.
Biff, the leader of the Hunters, and a few
other members with superior fighting
abilities, have exploited corruption to gain
power within the group. Despite this, the
majority of the Hunters struggle to
effectively use older firearms and rely on
the support of the empire.
Their leader, Biff, is accompanied by a
small group of loyal, corrupt convicts.
While the Hunters are technically
monitored by the empire, they have a
reputation for disregarding rules and
lacking discipline.
The Fidelian Empire considers
the Hunters to be an
invaluable part of their
military, and as such, they
regularly replenish their ranks
by selecting some of their
slaves to join the group.
These missions are typically
dirty or brutal tasks that the
empire cannot openly
perform, such as hunting
down escaped slaves or
suppressing survivor
settlements that do not
comply with the empire's
orders. The Hunters rely on
the empire for almost all of
their funding and rarely
interact with other groups.
They receive almost all of their requests
from the empire and rely on them for
their operating funds, as they rarely
interact with other groups.
Biff, the former slave camp's
mercenary commander, is a greedy
and cunning individual who was
previously enslaved by the empire.
However, due to his strength and
proper manners, the empire
recognized him and freed him,
giving him the task of leading the
Hunters.
The Hunters are typically assigned
dirty and brutal missions that the
empire cannot openly perform,
such as hunting runaway enslaved
people and suppressing survivors'
settlements that do not obey the
empire with minimal force.
The Fidelian Empire is facing a
chronic shortage of troops as it
works to strengthen the
organization.
With insufficient resources to
maintain and operate a regular
army, the empire has become
accustomed to hiring and using
understaffed soldiers.
The Hunters are an exclusive
military group tasked with
relatively simple duties.
Their weapons are mainly guns from the
pre-war era, which are obtained through
looting and procured by moving to and
from the desert. They are armed with these
weapons and have superior combat power
compared to other organizations.
Jack'N Boyz have a tendency to attack first,
believing that they will have the advantage in
victory. However, their fighting style is rarely
used in prolonged battles or against large
numbers of trained troops. Their victory
depends on being the first to spot the enemy
and the first to flee.
Each member is assigned to a subordinate unit based on their roles in
combat, search, and procurement. Combat units receive preferential
treatment compared to non-combat units. While the cadres and units are
nominally divided, all decisions are virtually made by Jack Grey.
Jack'N Boyz mostly live
in cars and motorcycles
and prefer to stay in one
place for short periods
of time.
As a result, many of
them have converted
camping cars or buses
into temporary living
quarters.
Their leader, Jack Grey, was the state sheriff of Dallas and had
a happy, harmonious family life after the war. His wife and
kids were the most important thing to him. However, his
happiness was short-lived when his family was tragically killed
by a violent gang.
The overwhelming guilt over being unable to protect his
family transforms Jack into a different person.
Mobility is a priority for Jack'N Boyz, who ride
motorcycles and drive classic Mustang-like
muscle cars. They dress in long, dark coats and
hats, with small patterns hanging from their
hats or coats like pins.
The organization consists of
approximately 100 to 150 people,
including individuals of various
ethnicities, criminals, ex-military
personnel, and mercenaries between
the ages of 20 and 35. They aim to bury
their own free culture beneath their
weapons and past.
Jack'N Boyz is an organization of outlaws
led by the criminal Jack Grey, who
escaped from Fidelia's prison. Most of the
initial members are from the Fidelian
Empire and were sentenced to death
under the strict laws of the empire, but
escaped with Jack Grey while serving
their sentences.
